questionsData.article:
Historians believe that Maya people of central America first learned to farm cacao plants around two
thousand years ago. The Maya people took the cacao trees from the rainforests and grew them in (their 1) gardens.
They cooked the cacao seeds, and then crushed them into a soft paste. They mixed the paste with water and spices
to make an unsweetened chocolate drink. The explorer, Colombus, brought cacao seeds to Spain after his trip to
central America in 1502. The wealthy people of Spain first enjoyed a sweetened version of chocolate drink. Later,
the popularity of the drink spread throughout Europe. Chocolate (remained 2) a drink that only (wealthy 3) people
could afford to drink until the 18th century. During the period known as the Industrial Revolution, new
technologies helped make chocolate less costly to produce. Today, chocolate making is a big business. Many offer
chocolate lovers the chance to taste chocolates grown in different areas of the world.
